T1  - ROHINGYA CRISIS CONCLUDING STATEMENT
AN  - 2376924335
AB  - On 27-28 July 2019, the Department of Political Science and Sociology and the South Asian Institute of Policy and Governance of North South University in Dhaka, Bangladesh, together with the United Nations High Commission for Refugees, sponsored and convened an international academic conference (a) to explore the challenges of responding to the Rohingya refugee crisis in southeast Bangladesh and (b) to consider reasonably practicable and sustainable solutions to the crisis. As noted in the Organizing Committee's call for papers, the Rohingya refugee crisis is an especially critical ongoing concern for Bangladesh as the host country, but also for the international community that provides humanitarian assis tance to more than a million refugees now living in temporary settlement camps. The significant financial and logistical burden of providing for the basic needs of men, women, and children is extraordinary under most circumstances of humanitarian care; but it is even more so in present case given that Bangladesh is a lower middle income country having little of its own resources disposable towards any long-term humanitarian assistance to the Rohingya. Clearly, these refugees await earnest conclusion of bilateral and multilateral diplomatic efforts with the hope of a voluntary and secure repatriation to their former homes in Myanmar. After two days of intense discussion in parallel sessions and plenaries engaging academics, government officials, and practitioners from the field, the Organizing Committee committed itself to providing this overview statement at the concluding session of the conference. It is important to provide the concerned public with a perspective on what was learned from this important meeting about both the challenges and the prospects for sustainable solution to the Rohingya crisis. The participants of the conference continue to believe, as was asserted even at the inception of the conference, that humanitarian action and national and regional security are inextricably linked. A feasible solution to the humanitarian crisis will have positive effect on the national security of the two principal countries involved as well as for regional political stability. Further, it is broadly recognized that while there are complex moral and legal issues of human rights to be settled, we uphold the principles of (1) non-refoulement and (2) a responsibility to protect persons rendered stateless due to armed conflict and forced displacement. We also assert a principled commitment to the undeniable fact that the Rohingya are a self-identifying ethnic group having verifiable historical roots in the territories from which they have been displaced. Accordingly, the Rohingya people have fundamental human rights that are to be protected as a matter of international law. We believe this to be so despite customary recognition of national sovereignty central to the policies adopted by both the government of Bangladesh and the government of Myanmar as they work to resolve the crisis.
